'''Carcathiocerta''' ({{Lang-hy|Կարկաթիոկերտ, Karkatiokert or Արկաթիակերտ, Arkatiakert}}; {{Lang-grc|Καρκαθιόκερτα, Karkathiokerta}}) was a city in [[Armenia]]n [[Sophene]] near the [[Tigris]], identified with the modern town of [[Eğil]]. It was the first capital of Sophene until [[Arsames I]] founded the new capital [[Arshamshat]] around 230 BCE. The Seleucid king [[Antiochus IV Epiphanes]] renamed the city into '''Epiphania'''.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} [[Strabo]] in his ''Geography'', calls it "The royal city of Sophene".<ref>{{Cite Strabo|11.14.3}}</ref> It was assigned to the late [[Roman Empire|Roman]] province of [[Mesopotamia (Roman province)|Mesopotamia]].<ref name=DARE/> It also bore the names '''Artagigarta''', '''Baras''', '''Basileon Phrourion''', and '''Ingila'''.<ref name=Barrington/> Under the name '''Ingila''', it became a bishopric; no longer the seat of a residential bishop, it remains a [[titular see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]].<ref>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/d2i22.html Catholic Hierarchy]</ref>

Its site is located at [[Eğil]] in [[Anatolia|Asiatic Turkey]].<ref name=Barrington>{{Cite Barrington|89}}</ref><ref name=DARE>{{Cite DARE|32727}}</ref>

